If an interviewer asks, "Why did you use FormData instead of useState?", you can answer:

"I used FormData because I only needed the form values when the user submitted the form. It keeps the code simpler and avoids creating separate state variables for each input. If I needed real-time validation or UI updates while the user types, I would use controlled components with useState instead."




Interview Question

Why do we use credentials: "include"?

Because browsers do not send cookies by default when making cross-origin requests. Setting:

credentials: "include"

tells the browser to send cookies (such as a JWT stored in an HTTP-only cookie) along with the request, allowing the server to identify the authenticated user. Without it, routes like /currentUser often return an unauthorized response even if the user has already logged in.



An HTTP-only cookie is a cookie that cannot be accessed by JavaScript (document.cookie). It can only be sent automatically by the browser in HTTP/HTTPS requests. This helps protect sensitive data like JWTs from being stolen through Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) attacks.



